This paper likely belongs to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) because it uses complex network methods to analyze patterns in the timing and configuration of reverts of article edits to Wikipedia, which is a large-scale temporal collaboration network. Additionally, the paper discusses negative social dynamics within the community of editors, which is a topic that falls under the scope of social and information networks. 

The paper could also belong to the sub-category of cs.SD (Software Engineering) because it discusses the knowledge collection practice conducted on Wikipedia, which is a software engineering problem. 

Furthermore, the paper could belong to the sub-category of cs.CY (Computers and Society) because it discusses the implications of negative social dynamics on the knowledge collection practice conducted on Wikipedia, which is a topic that falls under the scope of computers and society. 

The paper could also belong to the sub-category of cs.SOC (Social and Economic Networks) because it discusses social dynamics within a large-scale temporal collaboration network. 

Finally, the paper could belong to the sub-category of cs.HC (Human-Computer Interaction) because it discusses the behavior of editors on Wikipedia, which is a topic that falls under the scope of human-computer interaction.
